#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:6
msgid "pytest fixtures: explicit, modular, scalable"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:16
msgid ""
"`Software test fixtures`_ initialize test functions.  They provide a fixed "
"baseline so that tests execute reliably and produce consistent, repeatable, "
"results.  Initialization may setup services, state, or other operating "
"environments.  These are accessed by test functions through arguments; for "
"each fixture used by a test function there is typically a parameter (named "
"after the fixture) in the test function's definition."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:24
msgid ""
"pytest fixtures offer dramatic improvements over the classic xUnit style of "
"setup/teardown functions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:27
msgid ""
"fixtures have explicit names and are activated by declaring their use from "
"test functions, modules, classes or whole projects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:30
msgid ""
"fixtures are implemented in a modular manner, as each fixture name triggers "
"a *fixture function* which can itself use other fixtures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:33
msgid ""
"fixture management scales from simple unit to complex functional testing, "
"allowing to parametrize fixtures and tests according to configuration and "
"component options, or to re-use fixtures across function, class, module or "
"whole test session scopes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:38
msgid ""
"In addition, pytest continues to support :ref:`xunitsetup`.  You can mix "
"both styles, moving incrementally from classic to new style, as you prefer.  "
"You can also start out from existing :ref:`unittest.TestCase style <unittest."
"TestCase>` or :ref:`nose based <nosestyle>` projects."
msgstr ""

