#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:119
msgid "Fixtures as Function arguments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:121
msgid ""
"Test functions can receive fixture objects by naming them as an input "
"argument. For each argument name, a fixture function with that name provides "
"the fixture object.  Fixture functions are registered by marking them with :"
"py:func:`@pytest.fixture <_pytest.python.fixture>`.  Let's look at a simple "
"self-contained test module containing a fixture and a test function using it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:128
msgid ""
"# content of ./test_smtpsimple.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def smtp_connection():\n"
"    import smtplib\n"
"\n"
"    return smtplib.SMTP(\"smtp.gmail.com\", 587, timeout=5)\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_ehlo(smtp_connection):\n"
"    response, msg = smtp_connection.ehlo()\n"
"    assert response == 250\n"
"    assert 0  # for demo purposes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:146
msgid ""
"Here, the ``test_ehlo`` needs the ``smtp_connection`` fixture value.  pytest "
"will discover and call the :py:func:`@pytest.fixture <_pytest.python."
"fixture>` marked ``smtp_connection`` fixture function.  Running the test "
"looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:150
msgid ""
"$ pytest test_smtpsimple.py\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-5.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-0.x.y\n"
"cachedir: $PYTHON_PREFIX/.pytest_cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR\n"
"collected 1 item\n"
"\n"
"test_smtpsimple.py F                                                 [100%]\n"
"\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"________________________________ test_ehlo "
"_________________________________\n"
"\n"
"smtp_connection = <smtplib.SMTP object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"\n"
"    def test_ehlo(smtp_connection):\n"
"        response, msg = smtp_connection.ehlo()\n"
"        assert response == 250\n"
">       assert 0  # for demo purposes\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_smtpsimple.py:14: AssertionError\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"FAILED test_smtpsimple.py::test_ehlo - assert 0\n"
"============================ 1 failed in 0.12s ============================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:177
msgid ""
"In the failure traceback we see that the test function was called with a "
"``smtp_connection`` argument, the ``smtplib.SMTP()`` instance created by the "
"fixture function.  The test function fails on our deliberate ``assert 0``.  "
"Here is the exact protocol used by ``pytest`` to call the test function this "
"way:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:182
msgid ""
"pytest :ref:`finds <test discovery>` the ``test_ehlo`` because of the "
"``test_`` prefix.  The test function needs a function argument named "
"``smtp_connection``.  A matching fixture function is discovered by looking "
"for a fixture-marked function named ``smtp_connection``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:187
msgid "``smtp_connection()`` is called to create an instance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:189
msgid ""
"``test_ehlo(<smtp_connection instance>)`` is called and fails in the last "
"line of the test function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:192
msgid ""
"Note that if you misspell a function argument or want to use one that isn't "
"available, you'll see an error with a list of available function arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:198
msgid "You can always issue:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:200
msgid "pytest --fixtures test_simplefactory.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:204
msgid ""
"to see available fixtures (fixtures with leading ``_`` are only shown if you "
"add the ``-v`` option)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:207
msgid "Fixtures: a prime example of dependency injection"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:209
msgid ""
"Fixtures allow test functions to easily receive and work against specific "
"pre-initialized application objects without having to care about import/"
"setup/cleanup details. It's a prime example of `dependency injection`_ where "
"fixture functions take the role of the *injector* and test functions are the "
"*consumers* of fixture objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:220
msgid "``conftest.py``: sharing fixture functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:222
msgid ""
"If during implementing your tests you realize that you want to use a fixture "
"function from multiple test files you can move it to a ``conftest.py`` file. "
"You don't need to import the fixture you want to use in a test, it "
"automatically gets discovered by pytest. The discovery of fixture functions "
"starts at test classes, then test modules, then ``conftest.py`` files and "
"finally builtin and third party plugins."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:230
msgid ""
"You can also use the ``conftest.py`` file to implement :ref:`local per-"
"directory plugins <conftest.py plugins>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:234
msgid "Sharing test data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:236
msgid ""
"If you want to make test data from files available to your tests, a good way "
"to do this is by loading these data in a fixture for use by your tests. This "
"makes use of the automatic caching mechanisms of pytest."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:240
msgid ""
"Another good approach is by adding the data files in the ``tests`` folder. "
"There are also community plugins available to help managing this aspect of "
"testing, e.g. `pytest-datadir <https://pypi.org/project/pytest-datadir/>`__ "
"and `pytest-datafiles <https://pypi.org/project/pytest-datafiles/>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:248
msgid ""
"Scope: sharing a fixture instance across tests in a class, module or session"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:252
msgid ""
"Fixtures requiring network access depend on connectivity and are usually "
"time-expensive to create.  Extending the previous example, we can add a "
"``scope=\"module\"`` parameter to the :py:func:`@pytest.fixture <_pytest."
"python.fixture>` invocation to cause the decorated ``smtp_connection`` "
"fixture function to only be invoked once per test *module* (the default is "
"to invoke once per test *function*). Multiple test functions in a test "
"module will thus each receive the same ``smtp_connection`` fixture instance, "
"thus saving time. Possible values for ``scope`` are: ``function``, "
"``class``, ``module``, ``package`` or ``session``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:262
msgid ""
"The next example puts the fixture function into a separate ``conftest.py`` "
"file so that tests from multiple test modules in the directory can access "
"the fixture function:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:266
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"import smtplib\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"module\")\n"
"def smtp_connection():\n"
"    return smtplib.SMTP(\"smtp.gmail.com\", 587, timeout=5)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:277
msgid ""
"The name of the fixture again is ``smtp_connection`` and you can access its "
"result by listing the name ``smtp_connection`` as an input parameter in any "
"test or fixture function (in or below the directory where ``conftest.py`` is "
"located):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:282
msgid ""
"# content of test_module.py\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_ehlo(smtp_connection):\n"
"    response, msg = smtp_connection.ehlo()\n"
"    assert response == 250\n"
"    assert b\"smtp.gmail.com\" in msg\n"
"    assert 0  # for demo purposes\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_noop(smtp_connection):\n"
"    response, msg = smtp_connection.noop()\n"
"    assert response == 250\n"
"    assert 0  # for demo purposes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:299
msgid ""
"We deliberately insert failing ``assert 0`` statements in order to inspect "
"what is going on and can now run the tests:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:302
msgid ""
"$ pytest test_module.py\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-5.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-0.x.y\n"
"cachedir: $PYTHON_PREFIX/.pytest_cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR\n"
"collected 2 items\n"
"\n"
"test_module.py FF                                                    [100%]\n"
"\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"________________________________ test_ehlo "
"_________________________________\n"
"\n"
"smtp_connection = <smtplib.SMTP object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"\n"
"    def test_ehlo(smtp_connection):\n"
"        response, msg = smtp_connection.ehlo()\n"
"        assert response == 250\n"
"        assert b\"smtp.gmail.com\" in msg\n"
">       assert 0  # for demo purposes\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_module.py:7: AssertionError\n"
"________________________________ test_noop "
"_________________________________\n"
"\n"
"smtp_connection = <smtplib.SMTP object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"\n"
"    def test_noop(smtp_connection):\n"
"        response, msg = smtp_connection.noop()\n"
"        assert response == 250\n"
">       assert 0  # for demo purposes\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_module.py:13: AssertionError\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"FAILED test_module.py::test_ehlo - assert 0\n"
"FAILED test_module.py::test_noop - assert 0\n"
"============================ 2 failed in 0.12s ============================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:342
msgid ""
"You see the two ``assert 0`` failing and more importantly you can also see "
"that the same (module-scoped) ``smtp_connection`` object was passed into the "
"two test functions because pytest shows the incoming argument values in the "
"traceback.  As a result, the two test functions using ``smtp_connection`` "
"run as quick as a single one because they reuse the same instance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:348
msgid ""
"If you decide that you rather want to have a session-scoped "
"``smtp_connection`` instance, you can simply declare it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:351
msgid ""
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"session\")\n"
"def smtp_connection():\n"
"    # the returned fixture value will be shared for\n"
"    # all tests needing it\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:359
msgid ""
"Finally, the ``class`` scope will invoke the fixture once per test *class*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:363
msgid ""
"Pytest will only cache one instance of a fixture at a time. This means that "
"when using a parametrized fixture, pytest may invoke a fixture more than "
"once in the given scope."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:368
msgid "``package`` scope (experimental)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:372
msgid ""
"In pytest 3.7 the ``package`` scope has been introduced. Package-scoped "
"fixtures are finalized when the last test of a *package* finishes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:376
msgid ""
"This functionality is considered **experimental** and may be removed in "
"future versions if hidden corner-cases or serious problems with this "
"functionality are discovered after it gets more usage in the wild."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:380
msgid ""
"Use this new feature sparingly and please make sure to report any issues you "
"find."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:386
msgid "Dynamic scope"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:390
msgid ""
"In some cases, you might want to change the scope of the fixture without "
"changing the code. To do that, pass a callable to ``scope``. The callable "
"must return a string with a valid scope and will be executed only once - "
"during the fixture definition. It will be called with two keyword arguments "
"- ``fixture_name`` as a string and ``config`` with a configuration object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:395
msgid ""
"This can be especially useful when dealing with fixtures that need time for "
"setup, like spawning a docker container. You can use the command-line "
"argument to control the scope of the spawned containers for different "
"environments. See the example below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:399
msgid ""
"def determine_scope(fixture_name, config):\n"
"    if config.getoption(\"--keep-containers\", None):\n"
"        return \"session\"\n"
"    return \"function\"\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=determine_scope)\n"
"def docker_container():\n"
"    yield spawn_container()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:414
msgid "Order: Higher-scoped fixtures are instantiated first"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:418
msgid ""
"Within a function request for features, fixture of higher-scopes (such as "
"``session``) are instantiated first than lower-scoped fixtures (such as "
"``function`` or ``class``). The relative order of fixtures of same scope "
"follows the declared order in the test function and honours dependencies "
"between fixtures. Autouse fixtures will be instantiated before explicitly "
"used fixtures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:423
msgid "Consider the code below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:425
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"# fixtures documentation order example\n"
"order = []\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"session\")\n"
"def s1():\n"
"    order.append(\"s1\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"module\")\n"
"def m1():\n"
"    order.append(\"m1\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def f1(f3):\n"
"    order.append(\"f1\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def f3():\n"
"    order.append(\"f3\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(autouse=True)\n"
"def a1():\n"
"    order.append(\"a1\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def f2():\n"
"    order.append(\"f2\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_order(f1, m1, f2, s1):\n"
"    assert order == [\"s1\", \"m1\", \"a1\", \"f3\", \"f1\", \"f2\"]\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:427
msgid ""
"The fixtures requested by ``test_order`` will be instantiated in the "
"following order:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:429
msgid "``s1``: is the highest-scoped fixture (``session``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:430
msgid "``m1``: is the second highest-scoped fixture (``module``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:431
msgid ""
"``a1``: is a ``function``-scoped ``autouse`` fixture: it will be "
"instantiated before other fixtures within the same scope."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:433
msgid ""
"``f3``: is a ``function``-scoped fixture, required by ``f1``: it needs to be "
"instantiated at this point"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:434
msgid ""
"``f1``: is the first ``function``-scoped fixture in ``test_order`` parameter "
"list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:435
msgid ""
"``f2``: is the last ``function``-scoped fixture in ``test_order`` parameter "
"list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:441
msgid "Fixture finalization / executing teardown code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:443
msgid ""
"pytest supports execution of fixture specific finalization code when the "
"fixture goes out of scope.  By using a ``yield`` statement instead of "
"``return``, all the code after the *yield* statement serves as the teardown "
"code:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:447
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"\n"
"import smtplib\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"module\")\n"
"def smtp_connection():\n"
"    smtp_connection = smtplib.SMTP(\"smtp.gmail.com\", 587, timeout=5)\n"
"    yield smtp_connection  # provide the fixture value\n"
"    print(\"teardown smtp\")\n"
"    smtp_connection.close()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:462
msgid ""
"The ``print`` and ``smtp.close()`` statements will execute when the last "
"test in the module has finished execution, regardless of the exception "
"status of the tests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:466
msgid "Let's execute it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:468
msgid ""
"$ pytest -s -q --tb=no\n"
"FFteardown smtp\n"
"\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"FAILED test_module.py::test_ehlo - assert 0\n"
"FAILED test_module.py::test_noop - assert 0\n"
"2 failed in 0.12s"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:478
msgid ""
"We see that the ``smtp_connection`` instance is finalized after the two "
"tests finished execution.  Note that if we decorated our fixture function "
"with ``scope='function'`` then fixture setup and cleanup would occur around "
"each single test.  In either case the test module itself does not need to "
"change or know about these details of fixture setup."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:485
msgid ""
"Note that we can also seamlessly use the ``yield`` syntax with ``with`` "
"statements:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:487
msgid ""
"# content of test_yield2.py\n"
"\n"
"import smtplib\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"module\")\n"
"def smtp_connection():\n"
"    with smtplib.SMTP(\"smtp.gmail.com\", 587, timeout=5) as "
"smtp_connection:\n"
"        yield smtp_connection  # provide the fixture value"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:501
msgid ""
"The ``smtp_connection`` connection will be closed after the test finished "
"execution because the ``smtp_connection`` object automatically closes when "
"the ``with`` statement ends."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:505
msgid ""
"Using the contextlib.ExitStack context manager finalizers will always be "
"called regardless if the fixture *setup* code raises an exception. This is "
"handy to properly close all resources created by a fixture even if one of "
"them fails to be created/acquired:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:509
msgid ""
"# content of test_yield3.py\n"
"\n"
"import contextlib\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@contextlib.contextmanager\n"
"def connect(port):\n"
"    ...  # create connection\n"
"    yield\n"
"    ...  # close connection\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def equipments():\n"
"    with contextlib.ExitStack() as stack:\n"
"        yield [stack.enter_context(connect(port)) for port in (\"C1\", "
"\"C3\", \"C28\")]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:530
msgid ""
"In the example above, if ``\"C28\"`` fails with an exception, ``\"C1\"`` and "
"``\"C3\"`` will still be properly closed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:533
msgid ""
"Note that if an exception happens during the *setup* code (before the "
"``yield`` keyword), the *teardown* code (after the ``yield``) will not be "
"called."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:536
msgid ""
"An alternative option for executing *teardown* code is to make use of the "
"``addfinalizer`` method of the `request-context`_ object to register "
"finalization functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:540
msgid ""
"Here's the ``smtp_connection`` fixture changed to use ``addfinalizer`` for "
"cleanup:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:542
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"import smtplib\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"module\")\n"
"def smtp_connection(request):\n"
"    smtp_connection = smtplib.SMTP(\"smtp.gmail.com\", 587, timeout=5)\n"
"\n"
"    def fin():\n"
"        print(\"teardown smtp_connection\")\n"
"        smtp_connection.close()\n"
"\n"
"    request.addfinalizer(fin)\n"
"    return smtp_connection  # provide the fixture value"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:561
msgid ""
"Here's the ``equipments`` fixture changed to use ``addfinalizer`` for "
"cleanup:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:563
msgid ""
"# content of test_yield3.py\n"
"\n"
"import contextlib\n"
"import functools\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@contextlib.contextmanager\n"
"def connect(port):\n"
"    ...  # create connection\n"
"    yield\n"
"    ...  # close connection\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def equipments(request):\n"
"    r = []\n"
"    for port in (\"C1\", \"C3\", \"C28\"):\n"
"        cm = connect(port)\n"
"        equip = cm.__enter__()\n"
"        request.addfinalizer(functools.partial(cm.__exit__, None, None, "
"None))\n"
"        r.append(equip)\n"
"    return r"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:591
msgid ""
"Both ``yield`` and ``addfinalizer`` methods work similarly by calling their "
"code after the test ends. Of course, if an exception happens before the "
"finalize function is registered then it will not be executed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:599
msgid "Fixtures can introspect the requesting test context"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:601
msgid ""
"Fixture functions can accept the :py:class:`request <FixtureRequest>` object "
"to introspect the \"requesting\" test function, class or module context. "
"Further extending the previous ``smtp_connection`` fixture example, let's "
"read an optional server URL from the test module which uses our fixture:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/fixture.rst:606
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"import smtplib\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"module\")\n"
